<doc id="705735" wikidata="Q1412148" url="?curid=705735" title="XInclude">
<text>XInclude is a generic mechanism for merging XML documents, by writing inclusion tags in the &quot;main&quot; document to automatically include other documents or parts thereof. The resulting document becomes a single composite XML Information Set. The XInclude mechanism can be used to incorporate content from either XML files or non-XML text files.

XInclude is not natively supported in Web browsers, but may be partially achieved by using some extra JavaScript code.

== Example ==
For example, including the text file codice_1:

 This document is published under GNU Free Documentation License

in an XHTML document:
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt;
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;
 xmlns:xi=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude&quot;&gt;
 &lt;head&gt;...&lt;/head&gt;
 &lt;body&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;&lt;xi:include href=&quot;license.txt&quot; parse=&quot;text&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
gives:
 &lt;body&gt;
 This document is published under GNU Free Documentation License
 &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
&lt;/syntaxhighlight&gt;

The mechanism is similar to HTML&#x27;s codice_2 tag (which is specific to the HTML markup language), but the XInclude mechanism works with any XML format, such as SVG and XHTML.

== See also ==
* XPath

